# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: belle-of-the-west
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An **album** is a collection of audio recordings (e.g., music) issued on a medium such as compact disc (CD), vinyl (record), or audio tape (like 8-track or cassette), or in digital format.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The album was the dominant format or unit of recorded music expression and consumption from the mid-1960s through to the early 21st century, a period that has been described in the industry as the *album era*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Vinyl LPs are still issued for certain album releases, though album sales in the 21st-century have been predominantly in CD and then downloadable (e.g.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The 8-track tape was the first tape format, widely used alongside vinyl, from 1965 until being phased out by 1983—it was gradually supplanted by the cassette tape over the 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The popularity of the cassette reached its peak during the late 1980s before declining sharply during the 1990s as it yielded market share to compact disc formats.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An enormous variety of albums are now more widely (often globally) available, and listening to an album has been made cheaper, more convenient and more popular, through such services.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Most albums are recorded in a recording studio, making them *studio albums*, although they may also be recorded at a concert venue, at home, in the field, or in a mix of these and other places.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The total time to record an album varies between a few hours and several years.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Recording usually requires several takes of each track, each component piece of the album: in each track, different parts may be recorded separately, and then brought or "mixed" together.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Recordings that are done in one take without overdubbing are termed "live", even when done in a studio.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Studios are built to absorb sound, eliminating reverberation, to assist in mixing different takes; other locations, such as concert venues and some "live rooms", have more reverberation, which creates a "live" sound.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Recordings, including live, when published may contain editing, sound effects, voice adjustments, and other manipulations of the sound that was initially recorded.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] With modern recording technology, including multitrack recording, various artists collaborating on a track or album can be recorded in separate rooms or at separate times, perhaps while listening through headphones to certain other parts recorded earlier.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Album covers and liner notes may accompany an album, the latter of these conveying additional information, such as song lyrics, biographical information on artists, analysis of the recording, or librettos in the case of classical music and opera recordings.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Historically, the term "album" was applied to a collection of various items housed in a book or photo album format.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In musical usage, the word was used for collections of short pieces of printed music from the early nineteenth century.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] This format evolved after 1948 into vinyl long-playing (LP) records played at 33+1⁄3 rpm; these contained some 22 minutes of sound per side, giving an approximate 45 minutes of music per LP record.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] When these LPs were introduced, a collection of pieces or songs on a single record was called an "album"; the word was extended to other recording media such as compact disc, MiniDisc, compact audio cassette, 8-track tape and digital albums as they were introduced.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An album would typically have more tracks than an extended play (EP) record, which might contain only a 'single' (a single track released on its own), or two or three songs released together.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An *album* (Latin *albus*, white), in ancient Rome, was a board chalked or painted white, on which decrees, edicts, and other public notices were inscribed in black.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] It was from this that in medieval and modern times, album came to denote a book of blank pages in which verses, autographs, sketches, photographs and the like are collected.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the early nineteenth century, "album" was occasionally used in the titles of some classical music sets, such as Robert Schumann's *Album for the Young,* Op 68, a set of 43 short pieces.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] With the advent of 78 rpm records in the early 1900s, the typical 10-inch disc could hold only about three minutes of sound per side, so almost all popular recordings were limited to around three minutes in length.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Classical-music and spoken-word items generally were released on the longer 12-inch 78s, playing around 4–5 minutes per side.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] For example, in 1924, George Gershwin recorded a drastically shortened version of his new seventeen-minute composition *Rhapsody in Blue* with Paul Whiteman and His Orchestra.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The recording was issued on both sides of a single record, Victor 55225 and ran for 8m 59s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] By about 1910, bound collections of empty sleeves with a paperboard or leather cover, similar to a photograph album, were sold as record albums that customers could use to store their records (the term "record album" was printed on some covers).
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] These albums came in both 10-inch and 12-inch sizes.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The covers of these bound books were wider and taller than the records inside, allowing the record album to be placed on a shelf upright, like a book, suspending the fragile records above the shelf and protecting them.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the 1930s, record companies began issuing collections of 78s by one performer or of one type of music in specially assembled albums, typically with artwork on the front cover and liner notes on the back or inside cover.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Most albums included three or four records, with two sides each, making six or eight compositions per album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] By the mid-1930s, record companies had adopted the album format for classical music selections that were longer than the roughly eight minutes that fit on both sides of a classical 12" 78 rpm record.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Initially the covers were plain, with the name of the selection and performer in small type.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In 1938, Columbia Records hired the first graphic designer in the business to design covers, others soon followed and colorful album covers became an important selling feature.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The 10-inch and 12-inch LP record (long play), or 33+1⁄3 rpm microgroove vinyl record, is a gramophone record format introduced by Columbia Records in 1948.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A single LP record often had the same or similar number of tunes as a typical album of 78s, and it was adopted by the record industry as a standard format for the "album".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] When Columbia introduced the Long Playing record format in 1948, it was natural the term album would continue.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Columbia expected that the record size distinction in 78s would continue, with classical music on 12" records and popular music on 10" records, and singles on 78s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Columbia's first popular 10" LP in fact was Frank Sinatra's first album, the four-record eight-song *The Voice of Frank Sinatra*, originally issued in 1946.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] RCA's introduction of the smaller 45 rpm format later in 1948 disrupted Columbia's expectations.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] By the mid-1950s, 45s dominated the singles market and 12" LPs dominated the album market and both 78s and 10" LPs were discontinued.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the 1950s albums of popular music were also issued on 45s, sold in small heavy paper-covered "gate-fold" albums with multiple discs in sleeves or in sleeves in small boxes.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Sinatra's "The Voice" was issued in 1952 on two extended play 45s, with two songs on each side, in both packagings.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The term "album" was extended to other recording media such as 8-track tape, cassette tape, compact disc, MiniDisc, and digital albums, as they were introduced.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] As part of a trend of shifting sales in the music industry, some observers feel that the early 21st century experienced the death of the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An average length of an album is roughly 40 to 80 minutes and varies between various music genres and artists; a typical rock-adjacent album is around 40 minutes, while electronic and hip-hop albums are generally on the longer side.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Historically, 40 minutes was the average album length in the vinyl era, as a regular 12-inch LP record could hold up to around 23 minutes of audio on each side, combining to 46 minutes total, though the viable limit has been pushed to 52 minutes in 1960s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Unusual records with longer playtimes were also achieved, such as Todd Rundgren's *Initiation* at 68 minutes, though the quality of such records typically suffers as a result.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The average album length increased considerably in the 1990s, largely due to the proliferation of CDs which can hold up to 80 minutes of audio, almost double that of vinyls, as well as the growing electronic and hip-hop scene, which took advantage of the longer playing times.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Since the 2010s, the increasing prevalence of digital media allowed the album's length to not be limited by the physical format, though the average length continued to be around 40 to 80 minutes due to the established length range being standardized as well as the revival of physical media.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] An album may contain any number of tracks.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the United States, The Recording Academy's rules for Grammy Awards state that an album must comprise a minimum total playing time of 15 minutes with at least five distinct tracks or a minimum total playing time of 30 minutes with no minimum track requirement.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the United Kingdom, the criteria for the UK Albums Chart is that a recording counts as an "album" if it either has more than four tracks or lasts more than 25 minutes.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Sometimes shorter albums are referred to as mini-albums or EPs.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Albums such as *Tubular Bells*, *Amarok*, and *Hergest Ridge* by Mike Oldfield, and Yes's *Close to the Edge*, include fewer than four tracks, but still surpass the 25-minute mark.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The album *Dopesmoker* by Sleep contains only a single track, but the composition is over 63 minutes long.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] There are no formal rules against artists such as Pinhead Gunpowder referring to their own releases under thirty minutes as "albums".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] If an album becomes too long to fit onto a single vinyl record or CD, it may be released as a double album where two vinyl LPs or compact discs are packaged together in a single case, or a triple album containing three LPs or compact discs.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Some musical artists have also released more than three compact discs or LP records of new recordings at once, in the form of boxed sets, although in that case the work is still usually considered to be an album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Material (music or sounds) is stored on an album in sections termed tracks.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A music track (often simply referred to as a track) is an individual song or instrumental recording.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The term is particularly associated with popular music where separate tracks are known as album tracks; the term is also used for other formats such as EPs and singles.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] When vinyl records were the primary medium for audio recordings a track could be identified visually from the grooves and many album covers or sleeves included numbers for the tracks on each side.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] On a compact disc the track number is indexed so that a player can jump straight to the start of any track.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] On digital music stores such as iTunes the term song is often used interchangeably with track regardless of whether there is any vocal content.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A track that has the same name as the album is called the title track.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the Korean music industry, the title track is used to refer to any song that has been promoted, such as a single, regardless of its title.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A **bonus track** (also known as a **bonus cut** or **bonus**) is a piece of music which has been included as an extra.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] This may be done as a marketing promotion or for other reasons.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] It is not uncommon to include singles, B-sides, live recordings, and demo recordings as bonus tracks on reissues of old albums, where those tracks were not originally included.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Online music stores allow buyers to create their own albums by selecting songs themselves; bonus tracks may be included if a customer buys a whole album rather than just one or two songs from the artist.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The song is not necessarily free, nor is it available as a stand-alone download, adding to the incentive to buy the complete album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In contrast to hidden tracks, bonus tracks are included on track listings and usually do not have a gap of silence between other album tracks.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Bonus tracks on CD or vinyl albums are common in Japan for releases by European and North American artists; since importing international copies of the album can be cheaper than buying a domestically released version, Japanese releases often feature bonus tracks to incentivize domestic purchase.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Commercial sheet music is published in conjunction with the release of a new album (studio, compilation, soundtrack, etc.).
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A matching folio songbook is a compilation of the music notation of all the songs included in that particular album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] It typically has the album's artwork on its cover and, in addition to sheet music, it includes photos of the artist.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Most pop and rock releases come in standard Piano/Vocal/Guitar notation format (and occasionally Easy Piano / E-Z Play Today).
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Rock-oriented releases may also come in Guitar Recorded Versions edition, which are note-for-note transcriptions written directly from artist recordings.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Vinyl LP records have two sides, each comprising one-half of the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] If a pop or rock album contained tracks released separately as commercial singles, they were conventionally placed in particular positions on the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] During the sixties, particularly in the UK, singles were generally released separately from albums.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Today, many commercial albums of music tracks feature one or more singles, which are released separately to radio, TV or the Internet as a way of promoting the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Albums have been issued that are compilations of older tracks not originally released together, such as singles not originally found on albums, A-sides of singles, or unfinished "demo" recordings.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Double albums during the seventies were sometimes sequenced for record changers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the case of a two-record set, for example, sides 1 and 4 would be stamped on one record, and sides 2 and 3 on the other.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The user would stack the two records onto the spindle of an automatic record changer, with side 1 on the bottom and side 2 (on the other record) on top.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Side 1 would automatically drop onto the turntable and be played.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] When finished, the tone arm's position would trigger a mechanism which moved the arm out of the way, dropped the record with side 2, and played it.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] When both records had been played, the user would pick up the stack, turn it over, and put them back on the spindle—sides 3 and 4 would then play in sequence.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Record changers were used for many years of the LP era, but eventually fell out of use.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] 8-track tape (formally Stereo 8: commonly known as the eight-track cartridge, eight-track tape, or simply eight-track) is a magnetic tape sound recording technology popular in the United States from the mid-1960s to the late 1970s when the Compact Cassette format took over.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The format is regarded as an obsolete technology, and was relatively unknown outside the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada and Australia.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Stereo 8 was created in 1964 by a consortium led by Bill Lear of Lear Jet Corporation, along with Ampex, Ford Motor Company, General Motors, Motorola, and RCA Victor Records.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] It was a further development of the similar Stereo-Pak four-track cartridge created by Earl "Madman" Muntz.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A later quadraphonic version of the format was announced by RCA in April 1970 and first known as Quad-8, then later changed to just Q8.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The Compact Cassette was a popular medium for distributing pre-recorded music from the early 1970s to the early 2000s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The first "Compact Cassette" was introduced by Philips in August 1963 in the form of a prototype.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Compact Cassettes became especially popular during the 1980s after the advent of the Sony Walkman, which allowed the person to control what they listened to.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The Walkman was convenient because of its size, the device could fit in most pockets and often came equipped with a clip for belts or pants.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The compact cassette used double-sided magnetic tape to distribute music for commercial sale.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The music is recorded on both the "A" and "B" side of the tape, with cassette being "turned" to play the other side of the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Compact Cassettes were also a popular way for musicians to record "Demos" or "Demo Tapes" of their music to distribute to various record labels, in the hopes of acquiring a recording contract.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Compact cassettes also saw the creation of mixtapes, which are tapes containing a compilation of songs created by any average listener of music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The songs on a mixtape generally relate to one another in some way, whether it be a conceptual theme or an overall sound.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] After the introduction of Compact discs, the term "Mixtape" began to apply to any personal compilation of songs on any given format.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The sales of Compact Cassettes eventually began to decline in the 1990s, after the release and distribution Compact Discs.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The 2010s saw a revival of Compact Cassettes by independent record labels and DIY musicians who preferred the format because of its difficulty to share over the Internet.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The compact disc format replaced both the vinyl record and the cassette as the standard for the commercial mass-market distribution of physical music albums.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] After the introduction of music downloading and MP3 players such as the iPod, US album sales dropped 54.6% from 2001 to 2009.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The CD is a digital data storage device which permits digital recording technology to be used to record and play-back the recorded music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Most recently, the MP3 audio format has matured, revolutionizing the concept of digital storage.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Early MP3 albums were essentially CD-rips created by early CD-ripping software, and sometimes real-time rips from cassettes and vinyl.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The so-called "MP3 album" is not necessarily just in MP3 file format, in which higher quality formats such as FLAC and WAV can be used on storage media that MP3 albums reside on, such as CD-R-ROMs, hard drives, flash memory (e.g. thumbdrives, MP3 players, SD cards), etc.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Most albums are **studio albums**—that is, they are recorded in a recording studio with equipment meant to give those overseeing the recording as much control as possible over the sound of the album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] They minimize external noises and reverberations and have highly sensitive microphones and sound mixing equipment.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Band members may record their parts in separate rooms or at separate times, listening to the other parts of the track with headphones to keep the timing right.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] In the 2000s, with the advent of digital recording, it became possible for musicians to record their part of a song in another studio in another part of the world, and send their contribution digitally to be included in the final product.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Recordings that are done in one, 'straight-through' take without overdubbing or multi-tracking are termed "live", even when done in a studio.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] However, the common understanding of a **live album** is one that was recorded at a concert with a public audience, even when the recording is overdubbed or multi-tracked.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] To help differentiate between the two categories, the descriptor "live-to-tape" is often used.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Concert or stage performances are recorded using remote recording techniques.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Albums may be recorded at a single concert, or combine recordings made at multiple concerts.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] They may include applause, laughter and other noise from the audience, comments by the performers between pieces, improvisation, and so on.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] They may use multitrack recording direct from the stage sound system (rather than microphones placed among the audience), and can employ additional manipulation and effects during post-production to enhance the quality of the recording.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Notable early live albums include the double album of Benny Goodman, *The Famous 1938 Carnegie Hall Jazz Concert*, released in 1950.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Live double albums later became popular during the 1970s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Appraising the concept in *Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies* (1981), Robert Christgau said most "are profit-taking recaps marred by sound and format inappropriate to phonographic reproduction (you can't put sights, smells, or fellowship on audio tape).
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Among the best selling live albums are Eric Clapton's *Unplugged* (1992), selling over 26 million copies, Garth Brooks' *Double Live* (1998), over 21 million copies, and Peter Frampton's *Frampton Comes Alive!* (1976), over 11 million copies.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A **solo album**, in popular music, is an album recorded by a current or former member of a musical group which is released under that artist's name only, even though some or all other band members may be involved.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The solo album appeared as early as the late 1940s.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A 1947 *Billboard* magazine article heralded "Margaret Whiting huddling with Capitol execs over her first solo album on which she will be backed by Frank De Vol".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] There is no formal definition setting forth the amount of participation a band member can solicit from other members of their band, and still have the album referred to as a solo album.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] One reviewer wrote that Ringo Starr's third venture, *Ringo*, "[t]echnically... wasn't a solo album because all four Beatles appeared on it".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Three of the four members of the Beatles released solo albums while the group was officially still together.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A performer may record a solo album for several reasons.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A solo performer working with other members will typically have full creative control of the band, be able to hire and fire accompanists, and get the majority of the proceeds.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] The performer may be able to produce songs that differ widely from the sound of the band with which the performer has been associated, or that the group as a whole chose not to include in its own albums.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Graham Nash of the Hollies described his experience in developing a solo album as follows: "The thing that I go through that results in a solo album is an interesting process of collecting songs that can't be done, for whatever reason, by a lot of people".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A solo album may also represent the departure of the performer from the group.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Promotional sampler albums are compilations.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A tribute or **cover album** is a compilation of cover versions of songs or instrumental compositions.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Its concept may involve various artists covering the songs of a single artist, genre or period, a single artist covering the songs of various artists or a single artist, genre or period, or any variation of an album of cover songs which is marketed as a "tribute".
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] A **posthumous album** is an album released after an artist's death.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] These albums are often compilation albums, which sometimes feature unreleased music by the deceased artists.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] However, posthumous albums can also be studio albums, live albums or solo albums that primarily contain previously unreleased material.
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Album releases that are posthumous which include new music often have mixed reviews (i.e., aside from *Greatest Hits* compilations).
[src:belle-of-the-west/album] Examples of successful posthumous album releases include Nirvana's 1994 first live album, *MTV Unplugged in New York*, the Notorious B.I.G.'s 1997 *Life After Death* (released sixteen days after his death), and more recently, Mac Miller's 2020 posthumous album, *Circles*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] AllMusic was launched as *All-Music Guide* by Michael Erlewine, a "compulsive archivist, noted astrologer, Buddhist scholar, and musician." He became interested in using computers for his astrological work in the mid-1970s and founded a software company, Matrix, in 1977.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In the early 1990s, as compact discs (CDs) replaced LPs and cassettes as the dominant format for recorded music, Erlewine purchased what he thought was a CD of early recordings by Little Richard.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] After buying it, he discovered it was a "flaccid latter-day rehash." Frustrated with the labeling, he researched using metadata to create a music guide.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 1990, in Big Rapids, Michigan, he founded *All Music Guide* with a goal to create an open-access database that included every recording "since Enrico Caruso gave the industry its first big boost".
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] The first *All Music Guide*, published in 1992, was a 1,200-page reference book, packaged with a CD-ROM, titled *All Music Guide: The Best CDs, Albums & Tapes: The Expert's Guide to the Best Releases from Thousands of Artists in All Types of Music*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] Its first online version, in 1994, was a text-based Gopher site.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] It moved to the World Wide Web as web browsers became more user-friendly.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] Erlewine hired a database engineer, Vladimir Bogdanov, to design the *All Music Guide* framework, and recruited his nephew, writer Stephen Thomas Erlewine, to develop editorial content.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 1993, Chris Woodstra joined the staff as an engineer.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] A "record geek" who had written for alternative weeklies and fanzines, his main qualification was an "encyclopedic knowledge of music".
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] AllMusic developed a list of 1,400 subgenres of music, a feature that became central to the site's utility.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In a 2016 article in *Tedium*, Ernie Smith wrote, "AllMusic may have been one of the most ambitious sites of the early-internet [sic] era—and it's one that is fundamental to our understanding of pop culture.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] Because the thing is, it doesn't just track reviews or albums.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] It tracks styles, genres, and subgenres, along with the tone of the music and the platforms on which the music is sold.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 1996, seeking to further develop its web-based businesses, Alliance Entertainment Corp. bought All Music from Erlewine for a reported $3.5 million.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] Alliance filed for bankruptcy in 1999, and its assets were acquired by Ron Burkle's Yucaipa Equity Fund.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 1999, All Music relocated from Big Rapids to Ann Arbor, Michigan, where the staff expanded from 12 to 100 people.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] By February of that year, 350,000 albums and two million tracks had been cataloged.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In late 2007, AllMusic was purchased for $72 million by TiVo Corporation (known as Macrovision at the time of the sale and as Rovi from 2009 until 2016).
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 2012, AllMusic removed all of Bryan Adams' info from the site per a request from the artist.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In 2015, AllMusic was purchased by BlinkX, later known as RhythmOne.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] The AllMusic database is powered by a combination of MySQL and MongoDB.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] The All Media Network produced the *All Music Guide: The Definitive Guide* (at first released as *The Experts' Guide*), which includes a series of publications about various music genres.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] It was followed by the *Required Listening* series and annual guides.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] Vladimir Bogdanov is the president and the main editor of the series.
[src:belle-of-the-west/allmusic] In August 2007, *PC Magazine* included AllMusic in its "Top 100 Classic Websites" list.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] The *American Songwriter* staff concentrates on fulfilling the original objective of the magazine as set forth in the first issue in August 1984: producing an insightful, intellectually intriguing magazine about the art and stories of songwriting.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] In 2004, the magazine, previously published by Jim Sharp, was sold to an investment group based in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] In 2011, Albie Del Favero took over the reins, "joining the team as Co-Publisher, and President of its parent company ForASong Media, LLC.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] Del Favero’s extensive background in media includes being founding publisher of the Nashville Scene.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] *American Songwriter* is distributed worldwide.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] The magazine holds six bi-monthly lyric contests.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] The winner of each contest receives a new Gibson acoustic guitar, a Shure SM58 microphone, and a feature in the magazine.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] One annual grand-prize winner for the 2014 contest will win a co-writing session with Ashley Monroe, and get a chance to record a demo at a leading Nashville studio.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] In 2019, *American Songwriter* was acquired by Savage Media.
[src:belle-of-the-west/american-songwriter] A special section of the website, Songwriter U, focuses on the business of songwriting and includes articles on royalty collection, marketing, touring, guitar instruction and lyric technique.
[src:belle-of-the-west/americana-folk-albums] It has since expanded to a 25-position chart.
[src:belle-of-the-west/americana-folk-albums] In May 2016, *Billboard* renamed the chart to "Americana/Folk Albums", with the increasing popularity of Americana music, giving more recognition to acts which lean more towards Americana than folk.
[src:belle-of-the-west/americana-folk-albums] Over the chart's fourteen-year history Bob Dylan holds the record for the most number-one albums with eight.
[src:belle-of-the-west/americana-folk-albums] Chris Stapleton has spent 190 weeks at the chart's peak with his five number-one albums, including the longest-running number-one in the chart's history *Traveller*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] LaVere was born in Shreveport, Louisiana, and grew up in Bethany, Louisiana, a small Texas–Louisiana border town in the Piney Woods region, nurtured by musical parents with a passion for traditional country music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] Her family moved 13 times by the time she entered high school, ultimately landing in Detroit where LaVere fronted the alt rockband Last Minute while still in her teens.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] The early 1990s found LaVere in Nashville as part of the burgeoning Lower Broadway scene, where she began to play upright bass as half of the popular roots duo The Gabe & Amy Show.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] By 1999, she had moved to Memphis where she began work at Sun Studio.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In early 2006, LaVere released her debut album *This World Is Not My Home* on indie label Archer Records to instant national acclaim.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] She was joined on her album by many accomplished artists, including southern bluesman Jimbo Mathus, formerly of the Squirrel Nut Zippers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] The *Los Angeles Daily News* raved at the time, "Something like this doesn't come along every day." LaVere also began a nascent acting career starting with her cameo as Rockabilly queen Wanda Jackson in *Walk The Line* and continued with featured role in Craig Brewer's *Black Snake Moan*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In 2007, LaVere went into the studio with producer, Jim Dickinson to record her second album, *Anchors & Anvils*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] Dickinson captured LaVere and band at his Zebra Ranch recording barn 'art project' in rural Mississippi.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] Archer Records released *Anchors and Anvils* in May 2007.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] Her second album rose to number six on the Americana Music Charts and earned LaVere a nomination for the Americana Music Association Awards' Best New Or Emerging Artist.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] She toured the United States from coast to coast, played a series of dates with The Swell Season, performed at the Austin City Limits Festival, and shared the stage at the Americana Music Conference with Lyle Lovett, Todd Snider, and others.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] On October 1, 2008, she opened for Seasick Steve at the Royal Albert Hall in London.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In 2009 she opened for musical group Lucero on their 1372 Overton Park US Tour and also toured as a special guest with Seasick Steve.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In 2011, LaVere released her third album *Stranger Me* to critical acclaim.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] *Spin Magazine* called it "the breakup album of the year." *Q Magazine*, the *Daily Mirror* and *The Sun* all awarded it four stars.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In July 2011, LaVere and her band (guitarist David Cousar, violinist/keyboardist Krista Wroten-Combest and drummer Shawn Zorn), promoted the UK release of *Stranger Me* in London and France.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] On September 28, 2011, LaVere was named "Best Singer in Memphis" for the second consecutive year by the city of Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In the spring of 2012, LaVere joined band leader Luther Dickinson (of The North Mississippi Allstars), guitarist Shannon McNally, banjo player Valerie June and drummer and fife player Sharde Thomas, in the quintet bluegrass group, The Wandering.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] They released their debut album "Go On Now, You Can't Stay Here", and spent the spring of 2012 touring after the record's release.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] LaVere and McNally have partnered up to tour as a duo in October 2012 as part of their "Chasing the Ghost" tour.
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In 2013 LaVere teamed up with Memphis musician John Paul Keith and longtime live drummer Shawn Zorn, performing and recording as "Motel Mirrors".
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] In 2014 Amy released her 6th Studio record "Runaway's Diary".
[src:belle-of-the-west/amy-lavere] To date Amy continues to tour and write music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The first issue of *Billboard* was published in Cincinnati, Ohio, by William Donaldson and James Hennegan on November 1, 1894.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Initially it covered the advertising and bill-posting industry and was known as ***Billboard Advertising***.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] At the time, billboards, posters, and paper advertisements placed in public spaces were the primary means of advertising.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Donaldson handled editorial and advertising, while Hennegan, who owned Hennegan Printing Co., managed magazine production.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The first issues were just eight pages long.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The paper had columns such as The Bill Room Gossip and The Indefatigable and Tireless Industry of the Bill Poster.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] A department for agricultural fairs was established in 1896.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The *Billboard Advertising* publication was renamed ***The Billboard*** in 1897.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] After a brief departure over editorial differences, Donaldson purchased Hennegan's interest in the business in 1900 for $500 (equal to $15,500 today) to save it from bankruptcy.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] On May 5, Donaldson changed the publication from a monthly to a weekly paper with a greater emphasis on breaking news.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] He improved editorial quality and opened new offices in New York, Chicago, San Francisco, London, and Paris, and also refocused the magazine on outdoor entertainment such as fairs, carnivals, circuses, vaudeville, and burlesque shows.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] A section devoted to circuses was introduced in 1900, followed by more prominent coverage of outdoor events in 1901.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] *Billboard* also covered topics including regulation, professionalism, economics and new shows.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] It had a "stage gossip" column covering the private lives of entertainers, a "tent show" section covering traveling shows and a subsection called "Freaks to Order".
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] As railroads became more developed, *Billboard* enabled a mail-forwarding system for traveling entertainers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The location of an entertainer was tracked in the paper's Routes Ahead column, and then *Billboard* would receive mail on the star's behalf and publish a notice in its Letter-Box column that it had mail for him or her.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] This service was first introduced in 1904 and became one of *Billboard*'s largest sources of profit and celebrity connections.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] By 1914, 42,000 people were using the service.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] It was also used as the official address of traveling entertainers for draft letters during World War I.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In the 1960s, when the service was discontinued, *Billboard* was still processing 1,500 letters per week.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 1920, Donaldson controversially hired black journalist James Albert Jackson to write a weekly column devoted to black performers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] According to *The Business of Culture: Strategic Perspectives on Entertainment and Media*, the column identified discrimination against black performers and helped validate their careers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Jackson was the first black critic at a national magazine with a predominantly white audience.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] According to his grandson, Donaldson also established a policy against identifying performers by their race.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The jukebox industry continued to grow through the Great Depression and was advertised heavily in *Billboard*, which led to even more editorial focus on music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The proliferation of the phonograph and radio also contributed to its growing music emphasis.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] *Billboard* published the first music hit parade on January 4, 1936 and introduced a Record Buying Guide in January 1939.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 1940, it introduced Chart Line, which tracked the best-selling records, and was followed by a chart for jukebox records in 1944 called Music Box Machine.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] By the 1940s, *Billboard* was more of a music-industry specialist publication.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The number of charts that it published grew after World War II, as new music interests and genres became popular.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] It had eight charts by 1987, covering different genres and formats, and 28 charts by 1994.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] By 1943, *Billboard* had about 100 employees.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The magazine's offices moved to Brighton, Ohio in 1946, then to New York City in 1948.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] A five-column tabloid format was adopted in November 1950 and coated paper was first used in *Billboard*'s print issues in January 1963, allowing for photojournalism.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Over time, subjects that *Billboard* covered outside of the music world formed the basis of separate publications: *Funspot* magazine was created in 1957 to cover amusement parks and *Amusement Business* was created in 1961 to cover outdoor entertainment.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In January 1961, *The Billboard* was renamed ***Billboard Music Week*** to emphasize its newly exclusive interest in music.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Two years later, it was renamed to simply *Billboard*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] According to *The New Business Journalism*, by 1984, Billboard Publications was a "prosperous" conglomerate of trade magazines, and *Billboard* had become the "undisputed leader" in music-industry news.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In the early 1990s, *Billboard* introduced *Billboard Airplay Monitors*, a publication for disc jockeys and music programmers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] By the end of the 1990s, *Billboard* dubbed itself the "bible" of the recording industry.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 1987, *Billboard* was sold again to Affiliated Publications for $100 million.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Billboard Publications Inc. became a subsidiary of Affiliated Publications called BPI Communications.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] As BPI Communications, it acquired *The Hollywood Reporter*, *Adweek*, *Marketing Week* and *Mediaweek*, and also purchased Broadcast Data Systems, a high-tech firm for tracking music airtime.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Private investors from Boston Ventures and BPI executives repurchased a two-thirds interest in Billboard Publications for $100 million, and more acquisitions followed.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 1993, it created a division known as Billboard Music Group for music-related publications.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 1994, Billboard Publications was sold to Dutch media conglomerate Verenigde Nederlandse Uitgeverijen (VNU) for $220 million.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] VNU acquired the Clio Awards in advertising and the National Research Group in 1997, as well as *Editor & Publisher* in 1999.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In July 2000, it paid $650 million to the publisher Miller Freeman.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] BPI was combined with other entities in VNU in 2000 to form Bill Communications Inc.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] By the time CEO Gerald Hobbs retired in 2003, VNU had grown substantially larger, but had a great deal of debt from the acquisitions.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] An attempted $7 billion acquisition of IMS Health in 2005 prompted protests from shareholders that halted the deal; it eventually agreed to an $11 billion takeover bid from investors in 2006.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] VNU changed its name to Nielsen in 2007, the namesake of a company that it had acquired for $2.5 billion in 1999.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] New CEO Robert Krakoff divested some of the previously owned publications, restructured the organization and planned some acquisitions before dying suddenly in 2007.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] He was subsequently replaced by Greg Farrar.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Nielsen owned *Billboard* until 2009, when it was one of eight publications sold to e5 Global Media Holdings. e5 was formed by investment firms Pluribus Capital Management and Guggenheim Partners for the purpose of the acquisition.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The following year, the new parent company was renamed Prometheus Global Media.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Three years later, Guggenheim Partners acquired Pluribus' share of Prometheus and became the sole owner of *Billboard*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In December 2015, Guggenheim Digital Media spun out several media brands, including *Billboard*, to its own executive Todd Boehly.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The assets operate under the Hollywood Reporter-Billboard Media Group, a unit of the holding company Eldridge Industries.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Timothy White was appointed editor-in-chief in 1991, a position that he held until his unexpected death in 2002.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] White wrote a weekly column promoting music with "artistic merit" while criticizing music with violent or misogynistic themes, and also reworked the publication's music charts.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Rather than relying on data from music retailers, new charts used data from store checkout scanners obtained by Nielsen SoundScan.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] White also wrote in-depth profiles on musicians, but was replaced by Keith Girard, who was subsequently fired in May 2004.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Girard and a female employee filed a $29 million lawsuit alleging that *Billboard* fired them unfairly with an intent to damage their reputations and that they experienced sexual harassment, a hostile work environment and a financially motivated lack of editorial integrity.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Email evidence suggested that human resources were given special instructions to watch minority employees.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The case was settled out of court in 2006 for an undisclosed sum.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In the 2000s, economic decline in the music industry dramatically reduced readership and advertising from *Billboard*'s traditional audience.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The publication's staff and ownership were also undergoing frequent changes.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 2004, Tamara Conniff became the first female and youngest-ever executive editor at *Billboard* and led its first major redesign since the 1960s, designed by Daniel Stark and Stark Design.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] During Conniff's tenure, *Billboard*'s newsstand sales jumped 10%, ad pages climbed 22% and conference registrations rose 76%.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 2005, *Billboard* expanded its editorial outside the music industry into other areas of digital and mobile entertainment.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] In 2006, after leading *Billboard*'s radio publication, former ABC News and CNN journalist Scott McKenzie was named editorial director across all *Billboard* properties.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Conniff launched the *Billboard* Women in Music event in 2007.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Bill Werde was named editorial director in 2008, and was followed by Janice Min in January 2014, also responsible for editorial content at *The Hollywood Reporter*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The magazine became more of a general-interest music-news source rather than solely an industry trade, covering more celebrity and fashion news.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Min hired Tony Gervino as editor although he did not have a background in the music industry.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Gervino was appointed editor-in-chief in April 2014.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] An NPR item covered a leaked version of *Billboard*'s annual survey, which it said had more gossip and focused on less professional topics than had prior surveys.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] For example, the magazine polled readers on a lawsuit that singer Kesha filed against her producer, alleging sexual abuse.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] A note from Min to the editorial staff indicated that senior vice president of digital content Mike Bruno would head the editorial department.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] On June 15, 2016, BillboardPH, the first *Billboard* chart company in Southeast Asia, mainly in the Philippines, was announced.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] On September 12, 2016, *Billboard* expanded into China by launching *Billboard China* in partnership with Vision Music Ltd.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] On September 23, 2020, it was announced that Penske Media Corporation would assume operations of the MRC Media & Info publications under a joint venture with MRC known as PMRC.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The joint venture includes the management of *Billboard*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] On January 13, 2024, *Billboard* shared the intent to expand further in Asia by announcing the launch of *Billboard Korea*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Since 1990 *Billboard* established the *Billboard* Music Awards, an awards ceremony honors top album, artist and single in a number of different music genres which achieved the highest results during the year form sales, streaming, radio airplay, touring, and social engagement.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] The data are taken from *Billboard* and its data partners, including MRC Data and Next Big Sound.
[src:belle-of-the-west/billboard-magazine] Through the years, *Billboard* has established several other awards and polls to honor different music genres, live performances, and artists.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2007, publisher and editor Bob Kieser launched *Illinois Blues Blast*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The publication began with an email list of approximately 1,000 subscribers.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The initial focus was on album reviews and performance schedules for artists in Illinois and the surrounding Midwest.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2008, the publication was rebranded as *Blues Blast Magazine*.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The shift coincided with the establishment of the annual Blues Blast Music Awards.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2013, the publication was inducted into the Chicago Blues Hall of Fame.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The magazine is a digital publication distributed weekly.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] Its editorial content focuses on the contemporary Blues scene and its history.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The magazine operates with a staff of over 20 writers and photographers, and has published over 900 consecutive weekly issues, which includes over 5,500 music reviews and 670 artist interviews.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The publications is the largest publicly available online repository of Blues information.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The Blues Blast Music Awards are an annual set of awards presented by the magazine since 2008.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] Although the Awards are noted for being the largest fan-voted awards in the Blues genre, its nominees are determined solely by a group of Blues music industry professionals, including music critics, journalists, festival promoters, music venue managers, producers, and musicians.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] According to the magazine, the Awards results in two forms of recognition for artists.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] First, since award nominees represent the "best of" choices from Blues critics, an artist is recognized as having earned the equivalent of a "critics' award" honor by being nominated.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] Second, because the award winners are determined by the votes of Blues fans, an artist is recognized as having won the equivalent of a "people's choice award" honor in the category they were nominated.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The Awards are hosted at a live ceremony featuring performances from the nominated artists.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] For its first several years, the ceremony was held at Buddy Guy's Legends in Chicago.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2023, the 16th annual awards were held for the first time in Peoria, Illinois, at the 3300 Event Center, and served as a fundraising benefit for the Sean Costello Memorial Fund for Bipolar Research.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The Awards has also presented the Sean Costello Rising Star Award, which was named in honor of blues musician Sean Costello.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The Awards recognize artists across a wide spectrum of blues sub-genres.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2024, Rick Estrin & The Nightcats won Contemporary Blues Album for *The Hits Keep Coming*, in a category that also included nominees Selwyn Birchwood and Anthony Geraci.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The award for Traditional Blues Album went to John Primer & Bob Corritore for *Crawlin' Kingsnake*, with other nominees including Nick Moss and Monster Mike Welch.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] Christone "Kingfish" Ingram was named Male Blues Artist, and Sue Foley was named Female Blues Artist.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] Other nominees have include Shemekia Copeland, Bobby Rush, Bai Kamara and Elvin Bishop.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] In 2025, the Blues Foundation honored *Blues Blast Magazine* with a Keeping the Blues Alive Award.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The award is presented to non-performing individuals and organizations for "significant contributions to the Blues world" and are determined by a panel of blues professionals based on merit.
[src:belle-of-the-west/blues-blast-magazine] The official citation recognized the magazine as a "dedicated voice for the blues community" and an "indispensable resource for blues fans".
